Problem

You can perform at most 2 transactions.

Example:
prices = [3,3,5,0,0,3,1,4]

One optimal solution:

Buy 3
Sell 5

Profit = 2

Buy 0
Sell 4

Profit = 4

Total = 6
What changed?

In Stock II, our state was (i, buy) because we only needed to know

Current day
Can buy?
Now that's not enough.

Suppose we've already completed 2 transactions.

Can we buy again?
❌ No.

So we need one extra piece of information.
New State
(i, buy, cap) where cap = transactions remaining

********* Rule: Decrease cap only when selling, not when buying.************


Base Cases

There are two now.

1. No more days

if(i == n)
    return 0;
2. No transactions left

if(cap == 0)
    return 0;

Even if prices go up later, we can't trade anymore.


State: dp[i][buy][cap]

Since i only depends on i+1, we only keep two 2×3 arrays.

ahead → stores i+1
curr → stores i

class Solution {
public:
    int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {

        int n = prices.size();

        vector<vector<int>> ahead(2, vector<int>(3, 0));
        vector<vector<int>> curr(2, vector<int>(3, 0));

        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {

            for (int buy = 0; buy <= 1; buy++) {

                for (int cap = 1; cap <= 2; cap++) {

                    if (buy) {

                        curr[buy][cap] = max( -prices[i] + ahead[0][cap],ahead[1][cap]);

                    } 
                      else {

                        curr[buy][cap] = max(prices[i] + ahead[1][cap - 1], ahead[0][cap]);

                    }
                }
            }

            ahead = curr;
        }

        return ahead[1][2];
    }
};
